<DIV><FONT size="1" style="font-size:1pt;color:white">Triferic:  A New Way to Treat Iron Deficiency and Anemia 2 ND GENERATION PARENTERAL IRON: 100% IMMEDIATELY BIOAVAILABLE</FONT></DIV>

<DIV><FONT size="1" style="font-size:1pt;color:white">  Triferic         Platform  2nd generation parenteral iron* : 100% immediately bioavailable iron and avoids iron toxicity                                               &#9642;  Platform technology that can potentially be applied for treatment of iron                                                  deficiency and anemia in a number of disease states Triferic Replaces Iron Losses by Directly Donating Iron to        Transferrin for Red Blood Cell Production &#9642; Current FDA-approved indication - maintain hemoglobin in HD-dependent                                                  CKD patients: infused with dialysis (dialysate) or over 3hrs IV (AVNU)                                                   &#8226;  Maintains a stable hemoglobin with no increase in ferritin levels                                                   &#8226;  Replaces recurring iron loss during dialysis:                                                    &#8226;  Safety profile similar to placebo                                                   &#8226;  No increase in inflammation or oxidative stress                                              &#9642;  Novel, physiologic mechanism of action &#8211; donates iron directly and                                                  immediately to transferrin for tissue utilization and red blood cell production                                                    &#8226;  Is not taken up by reticuloendothelial cells first                                                   &#8226;  Does not increase ferritin and hepcidin levels    Modified from Brittenham GM, Chapter 34. Disorders of Iron Homeostasis: Iron Deficiency and Iron Overload. o    In Hoffman R. and Furie B. eds. Hematology: Basic Principles and Practice. Saunders, 6th ed., 2013 High ferritin and hepcidin levels can increase iron storage and reduce iron                                                           uptake by transferrin                                                             &#8226;  Safety profile similar to placebo - no observed risk of oxidative stress, iron                                                       overload, increased infection risk or hypersensitivity reactions   *First generation I.V. iron oxide nanoparticles (IONP&#8217;s) were introduced for clinical use in the 1980&#8217;s (beginning with Imferon (HMW iron dextran))                                                                                                             7</FONT></DIV>

Iron   supplementation  &#8226; Met secondary endpoint of significantly   decreasing the mean change from baseline of   serum ferritin level  &#8226; Triferic replaces iron losses, maintains Hgb   concentrations, does not increase iron stores   and exhibits a safety profile similar to placebo    1) Fishbane SN, Singh AK, Cournoyer SH, et al. <DIV><FONT size="1" style="font-size:1pt;color:white">New Indication Opportunities for FPC  &#8226; Evaluated multiple potential new indication opportunities for FPC and treatment of iron deficiency   and/or anemia &#8226; FPC as an iron therapeutic has the potential to provide benefit in multiple disease states &#8226; Based on analysis of development considerations, economics and pricing, and regimen ergonomics   (continuous I.V. infusion or multiple bolus doses) &#8211; two leading opportunities have been identified:   &#8226; FPC for home infusion in patients requiring parenteral nutrition    &#8226; Currently iron requirements can only be met with in-office I.V. iron infusion visit (due to hypersensitivity risk),       whereas FPC could be safely administered via an infusion pump at home   &#8226; FPC to improve cardiac function in hospitalized acute congestive heart failure patients    &#8226; Parenteral IONP studies have consistently demonstrated meaningful benefit in CHF in the outpatient setting;       however release of iron from the liver is likely to be too slow to produce a benefit in hospital      &#8226; Because of the immediate bioavailability of iron, FPC may lead to improved function in a hospitalized patient       (average LOS ~5 days)                                                                           22</FONT></DIV>
